In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims October 2011 as National Cybersecurity Awareness Month. He emphasizes the importance of cybersecurity in today's society, as people rely on the Internet and digital tools for various aspects of their lives. The President highlights the need for a coordinated national response to major disruptive cyber events and proposes plans to strengthen the protection of critical infrastructure. He also mentions the development of a comprehensive international vision for the future of the Internet, focusing on the secure flow of information and the promotion of universal rights, privacy, and prosperity. The President acknowledges that securing networks and personal information is a shared responsibility and calls for collaboration between the public and private sectors. He mentions initiatives such as the National Strategy for Trusted Identities in Cyberspace and the "Stop. Think. Connect." campaign to improve cybersecurity for businesses and consumers. Finally, President Obama urges the people of the United States to recognize the importance of cybersecurity and participate in activities, events, and trainings to enhance national security and resilience.